abstract: This Brooklyn neighborhood is joining East Harlem and six other districts that Mayor Bill de Blasio’s administration will try to rezone to accommodate more housing.
snippet: This Brooklyn neighborhood is joining East Harlem and six other districts that Mayor Bill de Blasio’s administration will try to rezone to accommodate more housing.
lead_paragraph: Last week, Mayor Bill de Blasio took an early victory lap on his campaign pledge to build and preserve 200,000 units of affordable housing by 2024. City Hall announced that nearly 53,000 affordable apartments were saved or put in the pipeline for construction during the past two and a half years.

abstract: From firing marshmallow cannons to speaking of “gel electrophoresis,” President Obama has embraced science and championed it as a national priority.
snippet: From firing marshmallow cannons to speaking of “gel electrophoresis,” President Obama has embraced science and championed it as a national priority.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Obama has started initiatives to study the brain and gene-based diseases. He has led attacks on the Ebola virus and antibiotic resistance. Last month, he wrote an academic article in a prominent medical journal.

headline_print_headline: Obama to Leave the White House Nerdier Than He Found It

abstract: On a bus tour that is also taking her to another crucial state, Ohio, Mrs. Clinton continued her balancing act on the economy.
snippet: On a bus tour that is also taking her to another crucial state, Ohio, Mrs. Clinton continued her balancing act on the economy.
lead_paragraph: JOHNSTOWN, Pa. — On the second day of a three-day bus tour through Pennsylvania and Ohio, Hillary Clinton continued a balancing act: painting a relatively rosy picture of national progress under President Obama — in contrast to Donald J. Trump’s grim appraisal of the country’s state — while insisting there is much more to be done.

abstract: Rounding up some of the notable things that were said at the Democratic National Convention.
snippet: Rounding up some of the notable things that were said at the Democratic National Convention.
lead_paragraph: When someone is cruel or acts like a bully, you don’t stoop to their level. No, our motto is, when they go low, we go high.

abstract: In an anxious era, Democratic bromides won’t win over Americans deeply dissatisfied with their politicians.
snippet: In an anxious era, Democratic bromides won’t win over Americans deeply dissatisfied with their politicians.
lead_paragraph: If the last two weeks of our political life have seemed extra long, it is because we have gone through not two but four political conventions.

abstract: With Hillary Clinton’s historic nomination, Americans are confronting the country’s poor record of putting women in positions of power.
snippet: With Hillary Clinton’s historic nomination, Americans are confronting the country’s poor record of putting women in positions of power.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — First a black president and now, just maybe, a woman. Karen Willis, an African-American delegate to this week’s Democratic convention here, was exhilarated by the historic possibilities of Hillary Clinton’s election run, viewing it as a natural succession to Barack Obama’s eight years in power. But when it comes to persuading voters, she noted, Mrs. Clinton’s gender milestone was the one thing her party was likely to play down.
